---
layout: layouts/base.njk
title: Worked Example — Does Fine-Tuning a Small Model Actually Help?
description: A reproducible four-way ablation (base / +RAG / fine-tuned / both) of Apertus-8B on Swiss FINMA circular Q&A, scored deterministically on answer accuracy and exact Rz-citation. The kind of evaluation sysf.io runs at the start of every Pilot.
tags: writing
date: 2026-07-19
kicker: Report
listTitle: Does fine-tuning a small model actually help? A measured answer.
blurb: A reproducible four-way ablation of Apertus-8B on Swiss FINMA circular Q&A. Fine-tuning plus retrieval doubles the production bar (answer + exact citation) from 22.4% to 45.4% — scored deterministically, on public data, with the harness open-sourced.
faq:
  - q: Is this on your customers' data?
    a: "No — deliberately. It runs entirely on public FINMA circulars so anyone can reproduce it, and so we can publish it. In a Pilot the identical method runs on your documents, inside your environment, and the report stays yours."
  - q: Why is 45% the headline and not something higher?
    a: "Because it's honest. Short-form answer plus exact citation is a hard bar, and the setup is deliberately modest — one 8B model at 4-bit, one LoRA run, plain retrieval. The value of the report is the method and the deltas between arms, not a leaderboard number."
  - q: How is this scored — is there an LLM judge?
    a: "No LLM judge anywhere. FINMA circulars number every normative paragraph (Randziffer, Rz), so a correct citation is exactly checkable. Answer accuracy is string/number matching against a verified gold answer; citation is an exact Rz match. Every number is recomputed from frozen run records."
---
{% from "partials/components.njk" import sectionHead, faqList, cta %}
{% from "partials/charts.njk" import hbarChart %}

<section class="border-b border-ink-900/10 dark:border-white/10">
  <div class="container-x py-16 md:py-24">
    <p class="eyebrow">Worked example · Evaluation</p>
    <h1 class="mt-4 max-w-4xl text-4xl font-bold leading-[1.08] tracking-tightest text-ink-900 md:text-5xl dark:text-white">
      Does fine-tuning a small model actually help?
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg prose-muted md:text-xl">
      Not an opinion — a measurement. We took Apertus-8B and ran the same four-way ablation we run at the start of every <a class="link-underline" href="/concepts/evaluation/">Pilot</a>, on a task where the answer can be scored exactly: answering questions about Swiss FINMA circulars <em>with</em> a citation to the exact margin number it rests on. The result: fine-tuning plus retrieval doubles the production bar — 22.4% to 45.4%.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- The four arms -->
<section class="container-x py-20 md:py-28">
  {{ sectionHead("The setup", "Four systems, one open model.", "Same Apertus-8B, quantized identically to 4-bit, served identically. The only variable is what we added.") }}
  <div class="mt-10 grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-4">
    {% set arms = [
      {k:"A", t:"Base", d:"The open model, as shipped."},
      {k:"B", t:"+ Retrieval", d:"Base model with BM25 retrieval over the circulars."},
      {k:"C", t:"Fine-tuned", d:"LoRA-tuned on the task, no retrieval."},
      {k:"D", t:"Fine-tuned + retrieval", d:"The full system."}
    ] %}
    {% for a in arms %}
    <div class="rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm dark:border-white/10 dark:bg-ink-950 {{ 'ring-2 ring-red-500 ring-inset' if a.k == 'D' }}">
      <div class="font-mono text-sm text-swiss">{{ a.k }}</div>
      <h3 class="mt-2 text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">{{ a.t }}</h3>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm prose-muted">{{ a.d }}</p>
    </div>
    {% endfor %}
  </div>
  <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-sm text-ink-500">Two things are scored, both deterministically — no LLM judge: is the answer correct, and did it cite the correct Rz in the correct circular. The production bar is <strong class="text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-300">both at once</strong> — a right answer with a wrong or missing citation is a failure, because in regulated work it is one.</p>
</section>

<!-- Results table -->
<section class="border-y border-ink-900/10 bg-ink-900/[0.02] py-20 dark:border-white/10 dark:bg-white/[0.02] md:py-28">
  <div class="container-x">
    {{ sectionHead("The result", "Fine-tuning plus retrieval doubles the production bar.", "183 human-verified questions (101 German, 82 English, 10 circulars). Brackets are 95% confidence intervals.") }}

    <div class="mt-10">
      {% set legend = [
        {name:"Answer correct", cls:"bg-teal-300"},
        {name:"Answer + citation (production bar)", cls:"bg-teal-600"},
        {name:"Full system (D)", cls:"bg-red-600"}
      ] %}
      {% set groups = [
        {label:"A · Base", bars:[{v:37.2, cls:"bg-teal-300"}, {v:0.0, cls:"bg-teal-600"}]},
        {label:"B · + Retrieval", bars:[{v:63.4, cls:"bg-teal-300"}, {v:22.4, cls:"bg-teal-600"}]},
        {label:"C · Fine-tuned", bars:[{v:44.8, cls:"bg-teal-300"}, {v:1.6, cls:"bg-teal-600"}]},
        {label:"D · Fine-tuned + retrieval", note:"the full system", bars:[{v:80.9, cls:"bg-teal-300"}, {v:45.4, cls:"bg-red-600"}]}
      ] %}
      {{ hbarChart(groups, legend, "Read down the production-bar row: it is near-zero without retrieval (A, C), reaches 22.4% with retrieval alone (B), and only fine-tuning <strong class='text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-300'>and</strong> retrieval together reach 45.4% (D, in red). Full breakdown below.") }}
    </div>

    <div class="mt-10 overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full min-w-[680px] border-collapse text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-ink-900/15 text-left dark:border-white/15">
            <th class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">Metric</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink-500">A · base</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink-500">B · +RAG</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink-500">C · tuned</th>
            <th class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-swiss">D · tuned+RAG</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="divide-y divide-ink-900/10 dark:divide-white/10">
          {% set rows = [
            {m:"Answer + citation (production bar)", a:"0.0%", b:"22.4%", c:"1.6%", d:"45.4%", hi:true},
            {m:"Answer correct", a:"37.2%", b:"63.4%", c:"44.8%", d:"80.9%"},
            {m:"Citation correct", a:"1.1%", b:"39.9%", c:"2.2%", d:"50.3%"},
            {m:"Emits the required format", a:"2.2%", b:"0.0%", c:"100%", d:"100%"}
          ] %}
          {% for r in rows %}
          <tr class="{{ 'bg-swiss/[0.04]' if r.hi }}">
            <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-ink-900 dark:text-white">{{ r.m }}</td>
            <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-ink-500">{{ r.a }}</td>
            <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-300">{{ r.b }}</td>
            <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-ink-500">{{ r.c }}</td>
            <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-swiss">{{ r.d }}</td>
          </tr>
          {% endfor %}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Decomposition -->
<section class="container-x py-20 md:py-28">
  {{ sectionHead("What each layer buys", "The ablation stops anyone — us included — from hand-waving.", "Each card below pins one mechanism to a number in the table above.") }}
  <div class="mt-10 grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-3">
    {% set parts = [
      {t:"Retrieval enables citation", d:"Citation-correct goes from ~1% to ~40–50% only when retrieval is on. A model cannot cite a margin number it has never seen — so both no-retrieval arms sit near zero on the production bar, however well-trained."},
      {t:"Fine-tuning enables usable output", d:"The base model often knows the answer (63% with RAG) but emits the required, machine-parseable format just 2% of the time — 0% once retrieval fills the context and distracts it. The fine-tune nails the format 100% of the time. That gap is most of B → D."},
      {t:"The two compound", d:"Retrieval alone adds 22.4 points; fine-tuning alone adds 1.6. Together they add 45.4 — nearly double the sum of the parts. That interaction is the finding, and it's why we measure before we build."}
    ] %}
    {% for p in parts %}
    <div class="rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 bg-white p-8 shadow-sm dark:border-white/10 dark:bg-ink-950">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">{{ p.t }}</h3>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm prose-muted">{{ p.d }}</p>
    </div>
    {% endfor %}
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Concrete example -->
<section class="border-y border-ink-900/10 bg-ink-900/[0.02] py-20 dark:border-white/10 dark:bg-white/[0.02] md:py-28">
  <div class="container-x">
    {{ sectionHead("It looks like this", "Same question, same retrieved text.", "The base model isn't stupid — it's unreliable in shape. Reliability of shape is what separates a demo from a system.") }}
    <div class="mt-10 max-w-3xl space-y-6">
      <div class="rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm dark:border-white/10 dark:bg-ink-950">
        <p class="text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-300"><span class="font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">Q.</span> For banks, securities firms and financial groups, what is the minimum required equity capital at which the fully qualitative and quantitative requirements apply? <span class="text-ink-500">(gold: CHF 10 billion, Rz 6, FINMA-RS 2010/01)</span></p>
        <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
          <div>
            <div class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-ink-500">Base + RAG</div>
            <pre class="mt-2 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded bg-ink-900/[0.04] p-3 font-mono text-xs text-ink-700 dark:bg-white/[0.04] dark:text-ink-300">CHF 10 billion</pre>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-swiss">Right answer, no citation → fails</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-ink-500">Fine-tuned + RAG</div>
            <pre class="mt-2 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded bg-ink-900/[0.04] p-3 font-mono text-xs text-ink-700 dark:bg-white/[0.04] dark:text-ink-300">ANSWER: CHF 10 billion
SOURCE: FINMA-RS 2010/01 Rz 6</pre>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-swiss">Passes</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Honest limits -->
<section class="container-x py-20 md:py-28">
  {{ sectionHead("The honest limits", "What this doesn't claim.", "An evaluation you can trust is one that names where it's weak.") }}
  <div class="mt-10 max-w-3xl space-y-4 text-base prose-muted">
    <p><strong class="font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">45% is a floor, not a ceiling.</strong> One small model, 4-bit, a single modest LoRA run on ~500 examples, deliberately plain BM25 retrieval. Every one of those is a lever a real Pilot pulls.</p>
    <p><strong class="font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">Structured answers are the weak spot.</strong> Fine-tuned+RAG scores ~47–50% on numbers, durations and yes/no but 27% on multi-item list questions. Complete-set extraction is the obvious next target.</p>
    <p><strong class="font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">The method is the product, not the number.</strong> Your task, your documents, this exact ablation — run before you commit to production, so the go/no-go decision rests on measurement, not a promise.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="mt-8">
    <a href="https://github.com/chengmanov/apertus-finma-eval" class="btn-ghost" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Reproduce it on GitHub →</a>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- FAQ -->
<section class="border-t border-ink-900/10 py-20 dark:border-white/10 md:py-28">
  <div class="container-x grid gap-12 md:grid-cols-12">
    <div class="md:col-span-4">{{ sectionHead("FAQ", "About this report.") }}</div>
    <div class="md:col-span-7 md:col-start-6">{{ faqList(faq) }}</div>
  </div>
</section>

{{ cta("Want this on your task?", "Bring one workflow and the documents behind it. We'll build the evaluation set and run this ablation — on your data, in your jurisdiction.") }}
